\begin_body

\begin_layout Title
Quantitative Finance - Formula Sheet
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Transition probability functions
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection*
Forward Kolmogorov Equation (Fokker-Plank equation)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The variable 
\begin_inset Formula $y$
\end_inset

 takes the value 
\begin_inset Formula $y'$
\end_inset

 at time 
\begin_inset Formula $t'$
\end_inset

 but how did it get there?
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Graphics
	filename FKE.png

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula $\frac{\partial p}{\partial t'}=c^{2}\frac{\partial^{2}p}{\partial y'^{2}}$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This equation is to be used if there is some special state now and you want
 to know what could happen later.
 For example, you know the current value of 
\begin_inset Formula $y$
\end_inset

 and you want ot knwo the distribution of value at some later date.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This is a partial differential equation for 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

 as a function of 2 independent variables 
\begin_inset Formula $y'$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $t$
\end_inset

'.
 
\begin_inset Formula $y$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $t$
\end_inset

 are rather like parameters in this problem.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection*
Backward Kolmogorov Equation
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The backward equation will be usefull if we want to calculate probabilities
 of reaching a specified final state from various initial state.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Graphics
	filename BKE.png

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula $\frac{\partial p}{\partial t}+c^{2}\frac{\partial^{2}p}{\partial y{}^{2}}=0$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection*
Solving Kolmogorov Equation - to review
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection*
Forward Kolmogorov Equation 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Consider an arbitrary random walk for the the variable 
\begin_inset Formula $y$
\end_inset

:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula $dy=A(y,t)dt,+B(y,t)dX$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The transition probability density function 
\begin_inset Formula $p(y,t,y',t')$
\end_inset

 is defined by
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula $\mbox{Prob}\left(a<y'<b\mbox{at time }t'|y\mbox{ at time }t\right)=\int_{a}^{b}p(y,t,y',t')dy'$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
(that's the probability that the random variable 
\begin_inset Formula $y'$
\end_inset

 lies between 
\begin_inset Formula $a$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $b$
\end_inset

 at the time 
\begin_inset Formula $t'$
\end_inset

 ikn the future, given that it started out with values 
\begin_inset Formula $y$
\end_inset

 at time 
\begin_inset Formula $t$
\end_inset

)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
FKE for this arbitrary random walk: 
\begin_inset Formula $\frac{\partial p}{\partial t'}=\frac{1}{2}\frac{\partial^{2}}{\partial y'^{2}}(B(y',t')^{2}p)-\frac{\partial}{\partial y'}(A(y',t')p)$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection*
Steady-state distribution
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Some random walks have a stead-state distribution
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In the long run, as 
\begin_inset Formula $t'\rightarrow\infty$
\end_inset

, the distribution 
\begin_inset Formula $p(y,t;y',t')$
\end_inset

 as a function of 
\begin_inset Formula $y'$
\end_inset

 settles down to be independant of the starting state 
\begin_inset Formula $y$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $t$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
If 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{\infty}$
\end_inset

 exists, the it satisfies the Forward Kolmogorov Equation (FKE) with the
 time dependant term 
\begin_inset Formula $\frac{\partial p_{\infty}}{\partial t}=0$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
i.e.
 
\begin_inset Formula $\frac{1}{2}\frac{\partial^{2}}{\partial y'^{2}}(B(y',t')^{2}p_{\infty})-\frac{\partial}{\partial y'}(A(y',t')p_{\infty})=0$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Tips:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Use the fact that, if there is a steady state probability distribution 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{\infty}$
\end_inset

, then the time dependant term 
\begin_inset Formula $\frac{\partial p_{\infty}}{\partial t}=0$
\end_inset

 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Use the fact the 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{\infty}$
\end_inset

 is probability density function; as such its integral over 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

 is 1
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Use the fact that when 
\begin_inset Formula $y\rightarrow\infty$
\end_inset

(becomes large), we have 
\begin_inset Formula $\begin{cases}
p_{\infty}(y) & \rightarrow0\\
\frac{\partial p_{\infty}}{\partial y} & \rightarrow0
\end{cases}$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Don't forget constant of integration
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Stochastic calculus
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection*
Brownian Motion
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 is the 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

end result
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 of a random walk, up to time 
\begin_inset Formula $t$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset Formula $dX$
\end_inset

 is the increment in X over 
\begin_inset Formula $dt$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula $dX\thicksim\sqrt{dt}$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula $dX^{2}$
\end_inset

 term becomes 
\begin_inset Formula $dt$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula $dX_{1}dX_{2}=\rho dt$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In stochastic calculus, there are 2 variables: the time 
\begin_inset Formula $t$
\end_inset

 and the Brownian motion 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula $dF=\ldots dt+\ldots dX$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection*
Ito's Lemma for 
\begin_inset Formula $F(X)$
\end_inset

 ; 
\begin_inset Formula $X(t)$
\end_inset

 being the standard Brownian motion 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula $dF=\frac{dF}{dX}dX+\frac{1}{2}\frac{d^{2}F}{dX^{2}}dt$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula $F(X(t))=f(X(0))+\int_{0}^{t}\frac{dF}{dX}(X(\tau))dX(\tau)+\frac{1}{2}\int_{0}^{t}\frac{d^{2}F}{dX^{2}}(X(\tau))d\tau$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection*
Ito's Lemma for 
\begin_inset Formula $F(X,t)$
\end_inset

; 
\begin_inset Formula $X(t)$
\end_inset

 being the standard Brownian motion 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula $dF=\frac{dF}{dt}dt+\frac{dF}{dX}dX+\frac{1}{2}\frac{d^{2}F}{dX^{2}}dt$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection*
Ito's Lemma for 
\begin_inset Formula $F(S)$
\end_inset

; 
\begin_inset Formula $S(t)$
\end_inset

 being a Brownian motion (
\begin_inset Formula $dS=a(S)dt+b(S)dX)$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula $dF=\left[a(S)\frac{dF}{dt}+\frac{1}{2}b(S)^{2}\frac{d^{2}F}{dS{}^{2}}\right]dt+b(S)\frac{dF}{dS}dX$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection*
Ito's Lemma for 
\begin_inset Formula $F(St)$
\end_inset

; 
\begin_inset Formula $S(t)$
\end_inset

 being a Brownian motion (
\begin_inset Formula $dS=a(S,t)dt+b(S,t)dX)$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula $dF=\frac{dF}{dt}dt+\frac{dF}{dS_{1}}dS_{1}+\frac{dF}{dS_{2}}dS_{2}+\frac{1}{2}b_{1}^{2}\frac{\partial^{2}F}{\partial S_{1}^{2}}+\frac{1}{2}b_{2}^{2}\frac{\partial^{2}F}{\partial S_{2}^{2}}+\rho b_{1}b_{2}\frac{\partial^{2}F}{\partial S_{1}\partial S_{2}}$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula $dF=\frac{dF}{dt}dt+\frac{dF}{dS}dX+\frac{1}{2}\sigma^{2}S^{2}\frac{d^{2}F}{dS{}^{2}}dt$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection*
Special case
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection*
S geometric Brownian motion (
\begin_inset Formula $dS=μSdt+σSdX)$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $F=\log(S)$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula $dF=(\mu-\frac{1}{2}\sigma^{2})dt+\sigma dX$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula $S(t)=S_{0}\exp((\mu-\frac{1}{2}\sigma^{2})t+\sigma X(t))$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Stochastic differential equations
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Martingales
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection*
Probability measure
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Graphics
	filename prob_measure.png

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection*
Probabilities and Expectations
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{E}[h(X)]=\int_{\mathbb{R}}h(x)p(x)\; dx=\int_{\mathbb{R}}h(x)\; d(P(x))$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
where p if the PDF and P is the CDF
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
example:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula $h(x)=\left[x-K\right]^{+}=\max\left[x-K,0\right]$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
i.e.
 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{E}\left[\left[x-K\right]^{+}\right]=\int_{-\infty}^{\infty}\left[x-K\right]^{+}\; d(P(x))=\int_{K}^{\infty}(x-K)\; d(P(x))=\frac{1}{\sqrt{2\pi\sigma}}\int_{K}^{\infty}(x-K)\exp\left\{ -\frac{1}{2}\left(\frac{x-\mu}{\sigma}\right)^{2}\right\} dx$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection*
Properties of Conditional Expectations
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Linearity
\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{E}\left[aX+bY|\mathcal{F}\right]=a\mathbb{E}\left[X|\mathcal{F}\right]+b\mathbb{E}\left[Y|\mathcal{F}\right]$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Enumerate
Tower property (i.e Iterated Expectations):
\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Standard
If 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{F\subset\mathcal{G}}$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{E}\left[\mathbb{E}\left[X|\mathcal{G}\right]|\mathcal{F}\right]=\mathbb{E}\left[X|\mathcal{F}\right]$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Enumerate
Special case of Tower property
\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{E}\left[\mathbb{E}\left[X|\mathcal{F}\right]\right]=\mathbb{E}\left[X\right]$
\end_inset

 (
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

no filtration
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 is always a smaller set than any filtration)
\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Enumerate
Taking out what is known
\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Standard
if 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 is 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{F}$
\end_inset

-measurable, then the value of 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 is known once we know 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{F}$
\end_inset

.
 Therefore, 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{E}[X|\mathcal{F}]=X$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Enumerate
Taking out what is known (2)
\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Standard
by extension, if 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 is 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{F}$
\end_inset

-measurable but not 
\begin_inset Formula $Y$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{E}[XY|\mathcal{F}]=X\mathbb{E}[Y|\mathcal{F}]$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Enumerate
Independance
\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Standard
if 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 is independent from 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{F}$
\end_inset

, then knowing 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{F}$
\end_inset

 is useless to predict the value of 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

.
 Hence, 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{E}[X|\mathcal{F}]=\mathbb{E}[X]$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Enumerate
Positivity
\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Standard
if 
\begin_inset Formula $X\geq0$
\end_inset

 then 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{E}[X|\mathcal{F}]\geq0]$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Enumerate
Jensen's Inequaltiy
\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Standard
let 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 be a convex function, then 
\begin_inset Formula $f(\mathbb{E}[X|\mathcal{F}])\leq\mathbb{E}\left[f(X)|F\right]$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Subsubsection*
Martingales
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Martingales as a class of stochastic process
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Exponentional martingales, whoch are a specific and extremly useful example
 of martingale
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Equivalent martingale measures, where we look for a probability measure
 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{Q}$
\end_inset

 such that a given stochastic process 
\begin_inset Formula $S(t)$
\end_inset

 is a martingales under 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{Q}$
\end_inset

regardless of its nature under 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{P}$
\end_inset

.The correspondance between the measures 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{P}$
\end_inset

and
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{Q}$
\end_inset

 is done through a change of measure.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection*
Proving that a discrete time process is a martingale
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This is done in 2 steps:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
show that the expectation exists, i.e.
 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{E}\left[|X_{n}|\right]<\infty$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
show that the process is driftless, i.e.
 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{E}\left[X_{n}|\mathcal{F}_{m}\right]=X_{m}$
\end_inset

 for 
\begin_inset Formula $m<n$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Graphics
	filename discrete_time_martingale.png

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection*
Supermartingale / Submartingale
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
A discrete time stochastic process 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ M_{t}:t=0,\ldots,T\right\} $
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
such that 
\begin_inset Formula $M_{t}$
\end_inset

is 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{F}_{t}$
\end_inset

-measurable for 
\begin_inset Formula $t=0,\ldots,Y$
\end_inset

 is a supermartingale (submartingale) if 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{E}\left[|M_{t}|\right]<\infty$
\end_inset

 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
and 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{E}\left[X_{n}|\mathcal{F}_{m}\right]\leq X_{m}$
\end_inset

 (supermartingale) or 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{E}\left[X_{n}|\mathcal{F}_{m}\right]\geq X_{m}$
\end_inset

 (submartingale) 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection*
Markov vs.
 Martingale
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Markov processes and martingales are not synonymous.
 The martingale property states that the expected value at time t + 1 is
 the value realized at time t.
 The process is 
\series bold
driftless
\series default
.
 The Markov property implies that the expected value at time t + 1 does
 not depend on the history (trajectory) up to time t, but it may depend
 on the value at time t.
 The process is 
\series bold
memoryless
\series default
 (no path dependence).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection*
Martingale in continuous time
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
A discrete time stochastic process 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ M_{t}:t\in\mathbb{R}^{+}\right\} $
\end_inset

such that 
\begin_inset Formula $M_{t}$
\end_inset

 is 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{F}_{t}$
\end_inset

-measurable for 
\begin_inset Formula $t\in\mathbb{R}^{+}$
\end_inset

 is a martingale if
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{E}\left[|M_{t}|\right]<\infty$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{E}\left[M_{t}|\mathcal{F}_{s}\right]=M_{s}$
\end_inset

 for 
\begin_inset Formula $0\leq s\leq t$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection*
A Brownian Motion is a Martingale
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The Levy characterization defines a Brownian motion as a stochastic process
 
\begin_inset Formula $X(t)$
\end_inset

 that satisfies the following conditions:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
\begin_inset Formula $X(0)=0$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
the sample paths 
\begin_inset Formula $t\mapsto X(t)$
\end_inset

 are continuous
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate

\series bold
independent increments
\series default
: for 
\begin_inset Formula $t_{1}<t_{2}<t_{3}<t_{4}$
\end_inset

 the increments 
\begin_inset Formula $X_{t_{4}}-X_{t_{3}}$
\end_inset

and 
\begin_inset Formula $X_{t_{2}}-X_{t_{1}}$
\end_inset

 are independent
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate

\series bold
normally distributed increments
\series default
: 
\begin_inset Formula $X_{t}-X_{s}\thicksim N(0,|t-s|)$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection*
Ito Integrals are Martingales (Martingale Representation Theorem)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
if 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

 is a martingale, then there exists a function 
\begin_inset Formula $g(t,X_{t})$
\end_inset

 satisfying technical condition such that 
\begin_inset Formula $M_{T}=M_{0}+\int_{0}^{T}g(t,X_{t})\; dX_{t}$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection*
Expecation of Ito Integrals
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{E}\left[\int_{0}^{T}g(t,X_{t})\; dX_{t}\right]=0$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection*
Fubini's theorem
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We can usually exchange the order of integration between the time integral
 and the expectation so that
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{E}\left[\int_{0}^{T}f(X_{t})\; dt\right]=\int_{0}^{T}\mathbb{E}\left[f(X_{t})\right]\; dt$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection*
Properties of Ito Integrals
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Linearity 
\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula $\int_{0}^{T}(\alpha f(t)+\beta g(t))dX_{t}=\int_{0}^{T}\alpha f(t)dX_{t}+\int_{0}^{T}\beta g(t)dX_{t}$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Enumerate
Itô isometry
\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{E}\left[|\int_{0}^{T}f(t)dX_{t}|^{2}\right]=\mathbb{E}\left[\int_{0}^{T}|f(t)|^{2}dt\right]$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Enumerate
Martingale
\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{E}\left[\int_{0}^{T}f(t)dX_{t}|\mathcal{F}_{s}\right]=\int_{0}^{s}f(t)\; dX_{t}$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Subsubsection*
Proving that a Continuous Time Stochastic Process is a Martingale
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Let's consider some stochastic process 
\begin_inset Formula $Y(t)$
\end_inset

 solving the following SDE:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula $dY(t)=f(t)dt+g(t)dX(t)$
\end_inset

 with 
\begin_inset Formula $Y(0)=Y_{0}$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula $Y(t)$
\end_inset

 is a martingale if an only if 
\begin_inset Formula $\forall t\; f(t)=0$
\end_inset

; i.e 
\begin_inset Formula $dY(t)=g(t)dX(t)$
\end_inset

 (
\begin_inset Formula $Y$
\end_inset

 has to be driftless)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection*
Exponential martingales
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Let's consider some stochastic process 
\begin_inset Formula $Y(t)$
\end_inset

 solving the following SDE:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula $dY(t)=f(t)dt+g(t)dX(t)$
\end_inset

 with 
\begin_inset Formula $Y(0)=Y_{0}$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We define a new process 
\begin_inset Formula $Z(t)=e^{Y(t)}$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula $Z(t)$
\end_inset

 is a martingale only if it is a driftless process, this is only possible
 if 
\begin_inset Formula $f(t)=-\frac{1}{2}g^{2}(t)$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Because the stochastic process Z(t) is the exponential of another process
 (namely Y (t)) and because it is a martingale, we call Z(t) an exponential
 martingale.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Binomial model
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
This is equivalent to saying that the stock growth rate is irrelevant for
 option pricing
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
The stock volatility is very important in the valuation of options
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Delta hedging means choosing Δ such that the portfolio value does not depend
 on the direction of the stock
\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula $\varDelta=\frac{\mbox{Range of option payoffs}}{\mbox{Range of stock prices}}$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Standard
Properties of the 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

real
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 world:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
We know all about delta hedging and risk elimination
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
We are very sensitive to risk, and expect greater return for taking risk
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
We don’t value options by taking expectations
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Properties of the 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

risk-neutral
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 world:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
We don’t care about risk, and don’t expect any extra return for taking unnecessa
ry risk
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
We don’t ever need to estimate probabilities of events happening
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
We believe that everything is priced using simple expectations
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Graphics
	filename binomial.png

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Let’s choose them so that they have the same mean and standard deviation
 as our earlier lognormal random walk!
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
u, v and p will therefore be related to μ and σ.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
mean/drift: 
\begin_inset Formula $μSδt=puS+(1\text{−}p)vS\text{−}S$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
variance: 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma^{2}S^{2}δt=S^{2}(p(u\text{−}1\text{−}(pu+(1\text{−}p)v\text{−}1))^{2}+(1-p)(v-1-(pu+(1\text{−}p)v\text{−}1))^{2})$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Here is one (approximate) solution:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
\begin_inset Formula $u=1+\sigma\sqrt{δt}$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
\begin_inset Formula $v=1-\sigma\sqrt{δt}$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
\begin_inset Formula $p=\frac{1}{2}+\frac{\mu\sqrt{δt}}{2\sigma}$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We choose 
\begin_inset Formula $\varDelta$
\end_inset

 to that the portfolio 
\begin_inset Formula $(V+\varDelta S)$
\end_inset

 has the same value if S goes up or down.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula $V^{+}\text{−Δ}uS=V^{-}\text{−Δ}vS$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
i.e.
 
\begin_inset Formula $\text{Δ}=\frac{V^{+}-V^{-}}{(u-v)S}$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Present value:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula $\frac{1}{1+r\delta t}\left(V^{+}-u\times\frac{V^{+}-V^{-}}{(u-v)}\right)=\frac{1}{1+r\delta t}\left(V^{-}-v\times\frac{V^{+}-V^{-}}{(u-v)}\right)=V-\varDelta S=V-\frac{V^{+}-V^{-}}{(u-v)}\times S$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We obtain:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula $V=\frac{V^{+}-V^{-}}{u-v}+\frac{1}{1+r\delta t}\frac{(uV^{-}-vV^{+})}{(u-v)}$
\end_inset

or 
\begin_inset Formula $V=\frac{1}{1+r\delta t}(p'V^{+}+(1-p')V^{-})$
\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $p'=\frac{1}{2}+\frac{r\sqrt{\delta t}}{2\sigma}$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We call p' the risk-neutral probability.
 It’s like the real probability, but the real probability if the drift rate
 were r instead of μ.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Remark*
Observe that the risk-free interest plays two roles in option valuation.
 It’s used once for discounting to give present value, and it’s used as
 the drift rate in the asset price random walk.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Remark*
\begin_inset Graphics
	filename binomial_tree.png

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Remark*
if 
\begin_inset Formula $δt\text{→}0$
\end_inset

, we obtain the pricing equation 
\begin_inset Formula $\frac{\text{\partial V}}{\partial t}+\frac{1}{2}\sigma^{2}S^{2}\frac{\partial^{2}V}{\partial S^{2}}+rS\frac{\partial V}{\partial S}-rV=0$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Black-Scholes 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection*
Black-Scholes assumptions:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
The underlying follows a lognormal random walk with known volatility.
 In the original model it was constant.
 However we can extend to consider a time dependent volatility.
\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma=\sqrt{\frac{1}{T-t}\int_{t}^{T}\sigma^{2}(\tau)d\tau}$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
The short -term risk-free interest rate is a known function of time.
 Again, initially r was a constant, how ever we can incorporate the average
 of a time varying rate of interest.
\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula $r=\frac{1}{T-t}\int_{t}^{T}r(\tau)d\tau$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
There are no dividends on the underlying, nor does the stock pay any other
 cashows during the life of the option
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Delta hedging is done continuously
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
The market is frictionless/perfect liquidity
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
There are no arbitrage opportunities
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Construct the portfolio 
\begin_inset Formula $\Pi=V(St,t)-\varDelta S$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Use Ito to calculate 
\begin_inset Formula $dV=\frac{\partial V}{\partial t}dt+\frac{\partial V}{\partial S}dS+\frac{1}{2}\frac{\partial^{2}V}{\partial S^{2}}dS^{2}=\left(\frac{\partial V}{\partial t}dt+\frac{\partial V}{\partial S}dS+\frac{1}{2}\frac{\partial^{2}V}{\partial S^{2}}\right)dt+\sigma S\frac{\partial V}{\partial S}dW$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Then, we obtain 
\begin_inset Formula $d\Pi=\left(\frac{\partial V}{\partial t}dt+\frac{\partial V}{\partial S}dS+\frac{1}{2}\frac{\partial^{2}V}{\partial S^{2}}\right)dt+\sigma S\frac{\partial V}{\partial S}dW-\varDelta(\mu Sdt+\sigma SdW)$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We choose 
\begin_inset Formula $\varDelta$
\end_inset

 so that 
\begin_inset Formula $d\Pi$
\end_inset

 does not contain risk (i.e.
 term in from of 
\begin_inset Formula $dW$
\end_inset

 become zero): 
\begin_inset Formula $\varDelta=\frac{\partial V}{\partial S}$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Them we obtain 
\begin_inset Formula $d\Pi=\left(\frac{\partial V}{\partial t}dt+\frac{1}{2}\frac{\partial^{2}V}{\partial S^{2}}\right)dt$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
By using the no-arbitrage argument, we say that our portfolio 
\begin_inset Formula $\Pi$
\end_inset

 grows like money in the bank, i.e.
 it grows by 
\begin_inset Formula $r\Pi dt$
\end_inset

 during 
\begin_inset Formula $dt$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We obtain then 
\begin_inset Formula $d\Pi=\left(\frac{\partial V}{\partial t}dt+\frac{1}{2}\frac{\partial^{2}V}{\partial S^{2}}\right)dt=r\Pi dt=r(V-\varDelta S)dt=r\left(V-S\frac{\partial V}{\partial S}\right)dt$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
i.e.
 we obtain the BSE = 
\begin_inset Formula $\frac{\text{\partial V}}{\partial t}+\frac{1}{2}\sigma^{2}S^{2}\frac{\partial^{2}V}{\partial S^{2}}+rS\frac{\partial V}{\partial S}-rV=0$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
To solve the Black-Scholes PDE we need to impose suitable boundary and nal
 conditions.
 Until we do so the BSE knows nothing about what kind of option we are pricing.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
If we remind ourselves of the structure of this equation, i.e.
 .rst order in time and second order in asset price - this tells us that
 we need one time condition and two boundary conditions.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Final Condition provides information on t: This is called the Payoff.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Boundary Condition tells us something about the underlying for two values
 of S.
 In this case we choose 
\begin_inset Formula $S=0$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $S\rightarrow\infty$
\end_inset

 (i.e.
 when the underlying becomes large).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection*
Options on dividend-paying equities
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula $\frac{\text{\partial V}}{\partial t}+\frac{1}{2}\sigma^{2}S^{2}\frac{\partial^{2}V}{\partial S^{2}}+(r-D)S\frac{\partial V}{\partial S}-rV=0$
\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $D$
\end_inset

 is the dividend yield (pay 
\begin_inset Formula $DSdt$
\end_inset

 dividend for each time-step 
\begin_inset Formula $dt$
\end_inset

)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection*
Curreny Options
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula $\frac{\text{\partial V}}{\partial t}+\frac{1}{2}\sigma^{2}S^{2}\frac{\partial^{2}V}{\partial S^{2}}+(r-r_{f})S\frac{\partial V}{\partial S}-rV=0$
\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $r_{f}$
\end_inset

 is the foreign rate 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection*
Commodity options
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula $\frac{\text{\partial V}}{\partial t}+\frac{1}{2}\sigma^{2}S^{2}\frac{\partial^{2}V}{\partial S^{2}}+(r+q)S\frac{\partial V}{\partial S}-rV=0$
\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $q$
\end_inset

 is the cost of carry
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection*
Solving the Black-Scholes equation
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Three main steps:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Turn the BSE into a one dimensional heat equation by a series of transformations
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Use a known solution of the heat equation called the fundamental solution
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Reverse the transformations
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\series bold
Call option
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula $\mbox{Payoff}(S)=\max(S-E,0)$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula $V_{call}(S,t)=SN(d_{1})-Ee^{-r(T-t)}N(d_{2})$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula $d_{1}=\frac{log(S/E)+(r+\frac{1}{2}\sigma^{2})(T-t)}{\sigma\sqrt{T-t}}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $d_{2}=\frac{log(S/E)+(r-\frac{1}{2}\sigma^{2})(T-t)}{\sigma\sqrt{T-t}}=d_{1}-\sigma\sqrt{T-t}$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula $N(x)=\frac{1}{\sqrt{2\pi}}\int_{-\infty}^{+\infty}e^{-\frac{1}{2}\phi^{2}}d\phi$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Graphics
	filename call_options.png

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\series bold
Call Option (ATM forward)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Within the FX world At-The-Money-Forward (ATMF) options are the most heavily
 traded.
 When an option is struck ATMF, it means that the strike 
\begin_inset Formula $E=Se^{(r-r_{f})\tau}$
\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $\tau=T-t$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
it then simplifies 
\begin_inset Formula $d_{1}$
\end_inset

and 
\begin_inset Formula $d_{2}$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula $d_{1}=\frac{1}{2}\sigma\sqrt{\tau}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $d_{2}=-\frac{1}{2}\sigma\sqrt{\tau}$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Using the Kendall and Stuart (1943) approximation of the Normal CDF, we
 obtain
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula $C(S,t)\thickapprox0.4Se^{-r_{f}(T-t)}\sigma\sqrt{T-t}$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\series bold
Put option
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula $\mbox{Payoff}(S)=\max(E-S,0)$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula $V_{put}(S,t)=-SN(-d_{1})+Ee^{-r(T-t)}N(-d_{2})$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Graphics
	filename put_options.png

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\series bold
Put-call parity
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula $C-P=S-Ee^{-r(T-t)}$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\series bold
Binary options
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula $\mbox{Payoff}(S)=\mathcal{H}(S)=\begin{cases}
1 & S(T)\geq E\\
0 & \mbox{otherwise}
\end{cases}$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Graphics
	filename binary_options.png

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Cash-or-nothing
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula $C=e^{-r_{d}\tau}N(d_{2})$
\end_inset

 Foreign call / Domestic put
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula $P=e^{-r_{d}\tau}N(-d_{2})$
\end_inset

 Foreign put / Domestic call
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Asset-or-nothing
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula $C=e^{-r_{d}\tau}N(d_{1})$
\end_inset

 Foreign call / Domestic put
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula $P=e^{-r_{d}\tau}N(-d_{1})$
\end_inset

 Foreign put / Domestic call
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
The Greeks
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection*
Delta
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Graphics
	filename delta.png

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection*
Gamma
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
