\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Numerical methods
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection*
Monte Carlo
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The fair value of an option is the present vgalue of the expected payoff
 at expiry under the risk-neutral random walk for the underlying.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The risk-neutral random walk for 
\begin_inset Formula $S$
\end_inset

 is: 
\begin_inset Formula $dS=rSdt+\sigma SdX$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Justification:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Binomial method
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Black-Scholes Equation similar to backward Kolmogorow equation
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Martingale theory
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We can therefore write: 
\begin_inset Formula $\mbox{option value }=e^{-r(t-r)}\mathbb{E}\left[\mbox{payoff}(S)\right]$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The algorithm:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Simulate the risk-neutral random walk starting at today's value of the asset
 over the required horizon.
 This gives one realization of the underlying price path
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
For this realization, calculate the option payoff
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
perform many more such realization over the time horizon
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
calculate the average payoff over all realizations
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
tke the present value of this average, this is the option value
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\series bold
One giant leap: works in special cases
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
For the lognormal random walk we are lucky that we can find a simple and
 exact time stepping algorithm.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We can write the risk-neutral stochastic differential equation for 
\begin_inset Formula $S$
\end_inset

 in the form:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula $d(\log S)=(r-\frac{1}{2}\sigma^{2})dt+\sigma dX$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This can be integrated exactly to give
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula $S(t)=S(0)\exp((r-\frac{1}{2}\sigma^{2})t+\sigma\int_{0}^{t}dX)$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\series bold
Simulating the entire path: a method that always works
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Price paths are simulated using a discrete version of the SDE for 
\begin_inset Formula $S:$
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Formula $\delta S=rS\delta t+\sigma S\sqrt{\delta t}\times\phi$
\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi$
\end_inset

 is drawn from the standard normal distribution
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This way of simulating the time series is called the Eurler method.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
There are two (at least) sources of error in the Monte Carlo method:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
If the size of the time-step is 
\begin_inset Formula $\delta t$
\end_inset

, the we may introduce errors of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{O}(\delta t)$
\end_inset

 by virtue of the discrete approximation to continuous events
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Because we are only simulation a finite number of an infinitie number of
 possible paths, the error due to using 
\begin_inset Formula $N$
\end_inset

 realizations od the asset price paths is 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{O}(\frac{1}{\sqrt{N}})$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Advantages of Monte Carlo simulations:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
The mathematics that you need to perform can be very basic
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
correlation can be easily modeled and it is easy to price options on many
 assets (high-dimensional contracts)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
it is computationally quite efficient in high dimensions
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
there is plenty of software available; spreadsheets function that will suffice
 for mos the time
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
to get better accuracym just run more simulations
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Disadvantages of Monte Carlo simulations:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
The method is very slow, you need a lot of simulations to get an accurate
 answer
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Finding the greks can be hard
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
the method does not cope well with early exercise
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection*
Finite difference methods
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Graphics
	filename finite_diff_grid.png

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Grid definition:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula $\delta S=\frac{S^{*}}{N}$
\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $S^{*}\gg E$
\end_inset

 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula $\delta t=\frac{T}{M}$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Approximation of theta:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula $\frac{\partial V}{\partial t}(S,t)\thickapprox\frac{V_{i}^{k}-V_{i}^{k+1}}{\delta t}+\mathcal{O}(\delta t)$
\end_inset

 (forward difference)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Approximation of delta: 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula $\frac{\partial V}{\partial S}(S,t)\thickapprox\frac{V_{i+1}^{k}-V_{i}^{k}}{\delta S}+\mathcal{O}(\delta S)$
\end_inset

 (forward difference)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula $\frac{\partial V}{\partial S}(S,t)\thickapprox\frac{V_{i}^{k}-V_{i-1}^{k}}{\delta S}+\mathcal{O}(\delta S)$
\end_inset

 (backward difference)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula $\frac{\partial V}{\partial S}(S,t)\thickapprox\frac{V_{i+1}^{k}-V_{i-1}^{k}}{2\delta S}+\mathcal{O}(\delta S^{2})$
\end_inset

 (central difference)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Graphics
	filename diff_types.png

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Approximation of gamma:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula $\frac{\partial^{2}V}{\partial S^{2}}(S,t)\thickapprox\frac{V_{i+1}^{k}-2V_{i}^{k}+V_{i-1}^{k}}{\delta S^{2}}+\mathcal{O}(\delta S^{2})$
\end_inset

 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\series bold
Final conditions and payoffs
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula $V(S,T)=\mbox{Payoff}(S)$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
i.e.
 
\begin_inset Formula $V_{i}^{0}=\mbox{Payoff}(i\delta S)$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
for instance, for a call option: 
\begin_inset Formula $V_{i}^{0}=\max(i\delta S-E,0)$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\series bold
Boundary conditions
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Call option at 
\begin_inset Formula $S=0$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $S=0$
\end_inset

.
 Thus, we set 
\begin_inset Formula $V_{0}^{k}=0$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Call option for large S, the call value asymptotes to 
\begin_inset Formula $S-Ee^{-r(T-t)}$
\end_inset

.
 Thus, we set 
\begin_inset Formula $V_{i}^{k}=I\delta S-Ee^{-rk\delta t}$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Put option at 
\begin_inset Formula $S=0$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $V=Ee^{-r(T-t)}$
\end_inset

.
 Thus, we set 
\begin_inset Formula $V_{i}^{k}=Ee^{-rk\delta t}$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Put option for large S, the option become worthless.
 Thus, we set 
\begin_inset Formula $V_{i}^{k}=0$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
General condition at 
\begin_inset Formula $S=0$
\end_inset

.
 the diffusion and the dift term 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

switch off
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset Formula $\frac{\partial V}{\partial t}(0,t)-rV(0,t)=0$
\end_inset

.
 Thus, we set 
\begin_inset Formula $V_{0}^{k}=(1-r\delta t)V_{0}^{k-1}$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
General condition at infinity.
 the option has a pay that is linear in the underlying, i.e.
 
\begin_inset Formula $\frac{\partial^{2}V}{\partial S^{2}}(S,t)\rightarrow0$
\end_inset

 as 
\begin_inset Formula $S\rightarrow\infty$
\end_inset

.
 Thus, we set 
\begin_inset Formula $V_{i}^{k}=2V_{i-1}^{k}-V_{i-2}^{k}$
\end_inset

 (linear extrapolation)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection*
Finite Difference - Explicit scheme
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula $\frac{\partial V}{\partial t}+a(S,t)\frac{\partial^{2}V}{\partial S^{2}}+b(S,t)\frac{\partial V}{\partial S}+c(S,t)V=0$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula $\frac{\partial V}{\partial t}\thicksim\frac{V_{n}^{m}-V_{n}^{m-1}}{\delta t}$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula $\frac{\partial V}{\partial S}\thicksim\frac{V_{n+1}^{m}-V_{n-1}^{m}}{2\delta S}$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula $\frac{\partial^{2}V}{\partial S^{2}}\thicksim\frac{V_{n+1}^{m}-2V_{n}^{m}+V_{n-1}^{m}}{\delta S^{2}}$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Note: We define 
\begin_inset Formula $V_{n}^{m-1}$
\end_inset

as a function of 
\begin_inset Formula $V_{n+1}^{m},V_{n}^{m},V_{n-1}^{m}$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
we use the above approximations:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula $\frac{V_{n}^{m}-V_{n}^{m-1}}{\delta t}+a_{n}^{m}\times\frac{V_{n+1}^{m}-2V_{n}^{m}+V_{n-1}^{m}}{\delta S^{2}}+b_{n}^{m}\times\frac{V_{n+1}^{m}-V_{n-1}^{m}}{2\delta S}+c_{n}^{m}\times V_{n}^{m}=\mathcal{O}(\delta t,\delta S^{2})$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Backward 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This is an equation for 
\begin_inset Formula $V_{i}^{m-1}$
\end_inset

 (time 
\begin_inset Formula $m-1$
\end_inset

) given 3 option values at time 
\begin_inset Formula $m$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Graphics
	filename explicit_scheme.png

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Advantages of the explicit method:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
It is very easy to program and hard to make mistakes
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
When it does fo unstable it is usually quite obvious
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
It copes well with coefficients that are asset and/or time dependnet
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
it copes very well with early exercise
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
it can be used for modern option-pricing models
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The disadvantage of the explicit method:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
it is slower than Monte Carlo in high dimensions
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection*
Finite Difference - Implicit scheme
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Graphics
	filename implicit_scheme.png

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula $\frac{\partial V}{\partial t}\thicksim\frac{V_{n}^{m}-V_{n}^{m-1}}{\delta t}$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula $\frac{\partial V}{\partial S}\thicksim\frac{V_{n+1}^{m-1}-V_{n-1}^{m-1}}{2\delta S}$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula $\frac{\partial^{2}V}{\partial S^{2}}\thicksim\frac{V_{n+1}^{m-1}-2V_{n}^{m-1}+V_{n-1}^{m-1}}{\delta S^{2}}$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The BSE discretized and re-arranged gives us:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula $a_{n}\times V_{n-1}^{m-1}+b_{n}\times V_{n}^{m-1}+c_{n}\times V_{n+1}^{m-1}=V_{n}^{m}$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
where 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula $a_{n}=-\frac{1}{2}(\sigma^{2}n^{2}-n(r-D))\delta t$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula $b_{n}=1+(\sigma^{2}n^{2}+r)\delta t$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula $c_{n}=-\frac{1}{2}(\sigma^{2}n^{2}+n(r-D))\delta t$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This scheme has the same degree of accuracy than than the explict scheme
 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{O}(\delta t,\delta S^{2})$
\end_inset

 but its attraction lies in its stability: it is stable for all values of
 
\begin_inset Formula $\delta t$
\end_inset

.
 we say this scheme is 
\bar under
unconditionally stable
\bar default
.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\bar under
Boundary conditions
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
At 
\begin_inset Formula $S=0$
\end_inset

, i.e 
\begin_inset Formula $n=0$
\end_inset

, the BSE necomes 
\begin_inset Formula $(1+r\delta t)V_{0}^{m-1}=V_{0}^{m}$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
At 
\begin_inset Formula $n=N$
\end_inset

, i.e.
 
\begin_inset Formula $S\rightarrow\infty$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $\frac{\partial^{2}V}{\partial S^{2}}(S,t)\rightarrow\infty$
\end_inset

, we use vanishing gamma 
\begin_inset Formula $\Gamma\thicksim\frac{V_{n-1}^{m-1}-2V_{n}^{m-1}+V_{n+1}^{m-1}}{\delta S^{2}}=0$
\end_inset

.
 Upon re-arranging, 
\begin_inset Formula $V_{N+1}^{m-1}=2V_{N}^{m-1}-V_{N-1}^{m-1}$
\end_inset

 (linear interpolation)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
we then obtain a 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

special
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 BSE: 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{a}_{N}\times V_{N-1}^{m-1}+\hat{b}_{N}\times V_{n}^{m-1}=V_{N}^{m}$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
with
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{a}_{n}=N(r-D)\delta t$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{b}_{n}=1-(N-(r-d)-r)\delta t$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Graphics
	filename implicit_scheme_matrix.png

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
For each time-step, we must solve: 
\begin_inset Formula $A\times V^{m-1}=V^{m}$
\end_inset

, i.e.
 
\begin_inset Formula $V^{m-1}=A^{-1}\times V^{m},$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
How to resolve the inverting matrix problem:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
solved directly (LU decomposition)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
or iteratively (Jacovi, Gauss-Seidel or SOR)
\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Standard
dg
\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Subsection*
Finite Difference - Crank-Nicolson scheme
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Graphics
	filename crank_nicolson_scheme.png

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The Crank-Nicolson method whilst being unconditionally stable has the additional
 advantage that it is also second order accurate in time i.e.
 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{O}(\delta t^{2},\delta S^{2})$
\end_inset

 .
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Consider a PDE being satisfied at the midpoint 
\begin_inset Formula $(n\delta S,(m-\frac{1}{2})\delta t)$
\end_inset

 and replace 
\begin_inset Formula $V_{s}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $V_{SS}$
\end_inset

 by means of FD approximation at the 
\begin_inset Formula $m^{th}$
\end_inset

 and the 
\begin_inset Formula $(m-1)^{th}$
\end_inset

 time-steps, i.e.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula $\frac{1}{2}(m+(m-1))\rightarrow(m-\frac{1}{2})$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The method is regarded as an equally weighted average of the explicit and
 the the implicit schemes with advantage over both individual cases due
 to accuracy being 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{O}(\delta t^{2})$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The resulting difference equation is:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula $a_{n}\times V_{n-1}^{m-1}+b_{n}\times V_{n}^{m-1}+c_{n}\times V_{n+1}^{m-1}=A_{n}\times V_{n-1}^{m}+B_{n}\times V_{n}^{m}+C_{n}\times V_{n+1}^{m}$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
and the matrix inversion problem we solve is:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula $A\times V^{m-1}=B\times V_{m}$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection*
Finite Difference - The 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta$
\end_inset

-Method
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta$
\end_inset

-method is a generalisation of the Crank-Nicolson scheme to obtain a weigthed
 average of the two schemes with a weighted parameters 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta\in[0,1].$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
i.e.
 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta\times\mbox{implicit}+(1-\theta)\times\mbox{explicit}$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula $a_{n}\times V_{n-1}^{m-1}+b_{n}\times V_{n}^{m-1}+c_{n}\times V_{n+1}^{m-1}=A_{n}\times V_{n-1}^{m}+B_{n}\times V_{n}^{m}+C_{n}\times V_{n+1}^{m}$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Note: The Crank-Nicolson method is the 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta$
\end_inset

-method with 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta=\frac{1}{2}-\frac{\delta S^{2}}{12\delta t}$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection*
Milstein correction
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We have seen:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Euler-Maruyana: 
\begin_inset Formula $S_{t+\delta t}=S_{t}(1+r\delta t+\sigma\phi\sqrt{\delta t})$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Milstein: 
\begin_inset Formula $S_{t+\delta t}=S_{t}(1+r\delta t+\sigma\phi\sqrt{\delta t}+\frac{1}{2}\sigma^{2}(\phi^{2}-1)\delta t)$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Remark*
\begin_inset Formula $\frac{1}{2}\sigma^{2}(\phi^{2}-1)\delta t$
\end_inset

 is called the Milstein correction
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection*
Monte Carlo Integration
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Suppose 
\begin_inset Formula $h()$
\end_inset

 is some fuction such that 
\begin_inset Formula $f\;:\;[0,1]\rightarrow\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

.
 The problem is to evaluate the integral 
\begin_inset Formula $I=\int_{0}^{1}h(x)dx$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Standard
We have 
\begin_inset Formula $I=\int_{0}^{1}h(x)dx=\int_{0}^{1}h(u)p(u)du$
\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $p(u)$
\end_inset

 is the probability density function of a uniformly random variable 
\begin_inset Formula $U(0,1)$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Enumerate
Suppose 
\begin_inset Formula $f()$
\end_inset

 is some fuction such that 
\begin_inset Formula $f\;:\;[a,b]\rightarrow\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

.
 The problem is to evaluate the integral 
\begin_inset Formula $I=\int_{a}^{b}f(x)dx$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Standard
Change of variable to convert 
\begin_inset Formula $[a,b]$
\end_inset

 into 
\begin_inset Formula $[0,1]$
\end_inset

, i.e.
 substitution 
\begin_inset Formula $y=\frac{(x-a)}{(b-a)}$
\end_inset

.
 which gives 
\begin_inset Formula $dy=dx/(b-a)$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
i.e we have 
\begin_inset Formula $I=(b-a)\mathbb{E}\left[f(U\times(b-a)+a\right]$
\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $U\thicksim U(0,1)$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Enumerate
Suppose 
\begin_inset Formula $g()$
\end_inset

 is some fuction such that 
\begin_inset Formula $g\;:\;[0,\infty]\rightarrow\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

.The problem is to evaluate the integral 
\begin_inset Formula $I=\int_{0}^{\infty}g(x)dx$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Standard
Change of variable to convert 
\begin_inset Formula $[0,\infty]$
\end_inset

 into 
\family roman
\series medium
\shape up
\size normal
\emph off
\bar no
\strikeout off
\uuline off
\uwave off
\noun off
\color none
[0,1], i.e.
 subsitution
\family default
\series default
\shape default
\size default
\emph default
\bar default
\strikeout default
\uuline default
\uwave default
\noun default
\color inherit

\begin_inset Formula $y=\frac{1}{1+x}$
\end_inset

.
 which gives 
\begin_inset Formula $dy=-dx/(1+x)^{2}=-y^{2}dx$
\end_inset


\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset

i.e we have 
\begin_inset Formula $I=\int_{0}^{1}\frac{g(\frac{1}{y}-1)}{y^{2}}dy=\mathbb{E}\left[\frac{g(\frac{1}{U}-1)}{U^{2}}\right]$
\end_inset

= where 
\begin_inset Formula $U\thicksim U(0,1)$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Subsection*
Gaussian Integrals
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Use the fact that, 
\begin_inset Formula $\frac{1}{\sqrt{2\pi}}\int_{-\infty}^{\infty}\exp(-x^{2}/2)dx=1$
\end_inset

 (it's the probability density function of the standard normal distribution)
 to calculate integrals like 
\begin_inset Formula $J=\frac{1}{\sqrt{2\pi}}\int_{-\infty}^{\infty}f(x)\exp(-x^{2}/2)dx$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula $J$
\end_inset

 can estimated using monte carlo simualation.
 i.e.
 
\begin_inset Formula $J=\mathbb{E}\left[f(X)\right]\thicksim J_{N}=\frac{1}{N}\sum_{n=1}^{N}x_{n}^{2}$
\end_inset

with 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{n}\thicksim N(0,1)$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Exotics
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Graphics
	filename exotics.png

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\series bold
Continously sampled arithmetic average
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The final payoff is a function of 
\begin_inset Formula $A=\frac{1}{T}\int_{0}^{T}S(\tau)\; d\tau$
\end_inset

 but the running average, and hence our new state variable is 
\begin_inset Formula $A=\frac{1}{T}\int_{0}^{t}S(\tau)\; d\tau$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We need a theory for options with payoff depending on integrals.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We start by assuming that the underlying asset follows the lo-normal random
 walk: 
\begin_inset Formula $dS=\mu Sdt+\sigma SdX$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Imagine a contract that pays off at expiry 
\begin_inset Formula $T$
\end_inset

 an amount that is a funciton of the path taken by the asset between time
 zero and expiry.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Let us suppose that this path-dependent quantity can be represented by an
 integral of some function of the asset over the perdio zero to 
\begin_inset Formula $T$
\end_inset

:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula $I(T)=\int_{0}^{T}f(S,\tau)\; d\tau$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
for an arithmetic average, we have 
\begin_inset Formula $f\equiv S$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
for a geometric average, we have 
\begin_inset Formula $f\equiv\log S$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
You might think that we need to model and remember 
\begin_inset Formula $S$
\end_inset

 at every single moment between now and expiration.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
One can imagine that the value of the option is thertefore not only a function
 of 
\begin_inset Formula $S$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $t$
\end_inset

, but also a function of 
\begin_inset Formula $I$
\end_inset

; 
\begin_inset Formula $I$
\end_inset

 will be our new independent variable, called a 
\series bold
state variable
\series default
.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula $V(S,t)\rightarrow V(S,I,t)$
\end_inset

 i.e.
 adds an extra dimension
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula $I(t)=\int_{0}^{t}f(S,\tau)\; d\tau$
\end_inset

 i.e.
 
\begin_inset Formula $dI=f(S,t)dt$
\end_inset

 (note: 
\begin_inset Formula $I$
\end_inset

 is a smooth function except at discontinuities of f and its SDE has no
 stochastic term, i.e only a drift)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula $\Pi=V(S,I,t)-\varDelta S$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
the change is this portfolio is given by:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula $d\Pi=\left(\frac{\partial V}{\partial t}+\frac{1}{2}\sigma^{2}S^{2}\frac{\partial^{2}V}{\partial S^{2}}\right)dt+\frac{\partial V}{\partial I}dI+\left(\frac{\partial V}{\partial S}-\varDelta\right)dS$
\end_inset

 (no diffusion term 
\begin_inset Formula $\frac{\partial^{2}V}{\partial I{}^{2}}$
\end_inset

because no stochastic term in 
\begin_inset Formula $dI$
\end_inset

)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula $d\Pi=\left(\frac{\partial V}{\partial t}+\frac{1}{2}\sigma^{2}S^{2}\frac{\partial^{2}V}{\partial S^{2}}\right)dt+\frac{\partial V}{\partial I}f(S,t)dt+\left(\frac{\partial V}{\partial S}-\varDelta\right)dS$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Because, it is a traded asset, we can hedge (we work in complete market),
 we can set 
\begin_inset Formula $\varDelta=\frac{\partial V}{\partial S}$
\end_inset

 to eliminate the risk
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
now, using the no arbitrage argument, we can say that 
\begin_inset Formula $d\Pi=r\Pi dt$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
i.e.
 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(\frac{\partial V}{\partial t}+\frac{1}{2}\sigma^{2}S^{2}\frac{\partial^{2}V}{\partial S^{2}}+\frac{\partial V}{\partial I}f(S,t)\right)=r\Pi dt=r(V(S,I,t)-\varDelta S)dt=r(V-\frac{\partial V}{\partial S}S)dt$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
i.e.
 the BSE for Asian Options 
\begin_inset Formula $\frac{\partial V}{\partial t}+\frac{1}{2}\sigma^{2}S^{2}\frac{\partial^{2}V}{\partial S^{2}}+\frac{\partial V}{\partial I}f(S,t)+rS\frac{\partial V}{\partial S}-rV=0$
\end_inset

 (where 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 depends on the sampling method)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This is to be solved sbject to 
\begin_inset Formula $V(S,I,t)=\mbox{Payoff}(S,I)$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\series bold
Example : 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Payoff for the continuously sampled arithmetic average strike call option
 is 
\begin_inset Formula $\max(S-\frac{1}{T}\int_{0}^{T}S(\tau)d\tau,0)$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This can be written as 
\begin_inset Formula $I(T)\max(R-\frac{1}{T},0)$
\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $I(t)=\int_{0}^{t}S(\tau)d\tau$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $R(t)=\frac{S(t)}{\int_{0}^{t}S(\tau)d\tau}$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In vierw of the form of the payoff function, it seems plausible tothat the
 option value takes the form:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula $V(S,I,t)=I(t)W(R,t)$
\end_inset

 with 
\begin_inset Formula $R(t)=\frac{S(t)}{I(t)}$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We find that 
\begin_inset Formula $W$
\end_inset

 satisfies the following PDE:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula $\frac{\partial W}{\partial t}+\frac{1}{2}\sigma^{2}R^{2}\frac{\partial^{2}W}{\partial R^{2}}+R(r-R)\frac{\partial W}{\partial R}-(r-R)W=0$
\end_inset

 with final condition 
\begin_inset Formula $W(R,T)=\max\left(R-\frac{1}{T},0\right)$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\series bold
Discrete arithmetic average
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula $A_{M}=\frac{I_{M}}{M}=\frac{1}{M}\sum_{k=1}^{M}S(t_{k})$
\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

 is tht total number of sampling dates
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
updating rule: 
\begin_inset Formula $A_{i}=\frac{1}{i}S(t_{i})+\frac{i-1}{i}A_{i-1}$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\series bold
Generalization
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
An updating rule is an algorithm for defining the path-dependent quantity
 in terms of the current 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

state of the world
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
The path-dependent quantity is measured on the sampling dates 
\begin_inset Formula $t_{i}$
\end_inset

 and takes the value 
\begin_inset Formula $I_{i}$
\end_inset

for 
\begin_inset Formula $t_{i}\leq t\leq t_{i+1}$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
A the sampling date 
\begin_inset Formula $t_{i}$
\end_inset

, the quantity 
\begin_inset Formula $I_{i-1}$
\end_inset

 is updated according to a rule such as: 
\begin_inset Formula $I_{i}=F(S(t_{i}),I_{i-1},i)$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\series bold
Loop back options
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula $I_{i}=max(S(t_{i}),I_{i-1})$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Interest rate modelling
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection*
General knowledge
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
IRS par swap at time 
\begin_inset Formula $t$
\end_inset

: 
\begin_inset Formula $r_{swap}=\frac{1-Z(t,T_{N})}{\tau\sum_{i=1}^{N}Z(t,T_{i})}$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Graphics
	filename swap.png

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Graphics
	filename swap2.png

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Various approaches to interest-rate modeling:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Deterministic
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Black '76 (bonds are assumed to have a log-normal random walk)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Stochastic spot rate (spot rate models)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Multi factor
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Heath, Jarrow & Morton
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
LIBOR Market Model
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection*
Spot-rate models
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Define 
\begin_inset Formula $\Pi=V_{1}-\varDelta V_{2}$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Hence we get 
\begin_inset Formula $d\Pi=\frac{\partial V{}_{1}}{\partial t}dt+\frac{\partial V_{1}}{\partial r}dr+\frac{1}{2}w^{2}\frac{\partial^{2}V_{1}}{\partial r^{2}}dt-\varDelta\left(\frac{\partial V{}_{2}}{\partial t}dt+\frac{\partial V_{2}}{\partial r}dr+\frac{1}{2}w^{2}\frac{\partial^{2}V_{2}}{\partial r^{2}}dt\right)$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We choose 
\begin_inset Formula $\varDelta=\frac{\frac{\partial V_{1}}{\partial r}}{\frac{\partial V_{2}}{\partial r}}$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Using no arbitrage argument, we say 
\begin_inset Formula $d\Pi=r\Pi dt=r(V_{1}-\varDelta V_{2})dt=r(V_{1}-\frac{\frac{\partial V_{1}}{\partial r}}{\frac{\partial V_{2}}{\partial r}}V_{2})dt$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
we obtain 
\begin_inset Formula $\frac{\frac{\partial V{}_{1}}{\partial t}+\frac{1}{2}w^{2}\frac{\partial^{2}V_{1}}{\partial r^{2}}dt-rV_{1}}{\frac{\partial V_{1}}{\partial r}}=\frac{\frac{\partial V{}_{2}}{\partial t}+\frac{1}{2}w^{2}\frac{\partial^{2}V_{2}}{\partial r^{2}}dt-rV_{2}}{\frac{\partial V_{2}}{\partial r}}$
\end_inset

 (independent of 
\begin_inset Formula $T_{1}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $T_{2}$
\end_inset

)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We then conclude that the expression (subscript dropped) is 
\begin_inset Formula $\frac{\frac{\partial V}{\partial t}+\frac{1}{2}w^{2}\frac{\partial^{2}V}{\partial r^{2}}dt-rV}{\frac{\partial V}{\partial r}}=a(r,t)$
\end_inset

 (function or 
\begin_inset Formula $r$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $t$
\end_inset

, not dependent on 
\begin_inset Formula $T_{i}$
\end_inset

)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
without loss of generality, we decide to write 
\begin_inset Formula $a(r,t)=w(r,t)\lambda(r,t)-u(r,t)$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The fixed-income pricing equation become therefore:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\frac{\partial V}{\partial t}+\frac{1}{2}w^{2}\frac{\partial^{2}V}{\partial r^{2}}+(u-\lambda w)\frac{\partial V}{\partial r}-rV=0
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The four terms in this equation represent the following:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
time decay (
\begin_inset Formula $\frac{\partial V}{\partial t}$
\end_inset

)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
diffusion (
\begin_inset Formula $w^{2}$
\end_inset

)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
drift (
\begin_inset Formula $u-\lambda w$
\end_inset

)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
discounting (
\begin_inset Formula $-rV$
\end_inset

)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\series bold
Market Price of Risk
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Imagine that you hold an unhedged position in one bond with maturity date
 
\begin_inset Formula $T$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In a time step 
\begin_inset Formula $dt$
\end_inset

 this bond changes in value:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula $dV=\left(\frac{\partial V}{\partial t}+\frac{1}{2}w^{2}\frac{\partial^{2}V}{\partial r^{2}}+u\frac{\partial V}{\partial r}\right)dt+w\frac{\partial V}{\partial r}dX$
\end_inset

 (Ito applied on 
\begin_inset Formula $v(r,t)$
\end_inset

)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Therefore, we obtain
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula $dV=\left(rV+\lambda w\frac{\partial V}{\partial r}\right)dt+w\frac{\partial V}{\partial r}dX$
\end_inset

 (using the fact that 
\begin_inset Formula $\frac{\partial V}{\partial t}+\frac{1}{2}w^{2}\frac{\partial^{2}V}{\partial r^{2}}+u\frac{\partial V}{\partial r}-rV=rV+\lambda w\frac{\partial V}{\partial r}$
\end_inset

; from the Brond Pricing Equation)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula $dV-rVdt=\lambda w\frac{\partial V}{\partial r}dt+w\frac{\partial V}{\partial r}dX$
\end_inset

 (difference between return on a unhedged bond and the risk free return)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula $dV-rVdt=w\frac{\partial V}{\partial r}\left(\lambda dt+dX\right)$
\end_inset

 (for every unit of risk 
\begin_inset Formula $dX$
\end_inset

, we are getting the return 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda dt$
\end_inset

; excess amount)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
For fixed-income products, the real growth of the spot interest rate may
 be 
\begin_inset Formula $u(r,t)$
\end_inset

 but we price as if it were 
\begin_inset Formula $u(r,t)-\lambda(r,t)w(r,t)$
\end_inset

 (risk adjusted drift rate).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In return for taking the risk the portfolio profits by 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda dt$
\end_inset

 per unit of risk 
\begin_inset Formula $dX$
\end_inset

.
 The function 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda$
\end_inset

 is called the market price of risk.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\series bold
Final condition for a ZCB:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula $V(r,T)=1$
\end_inset

 (redemption value scaled to 1)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\series bold
Relationship between pruices and expectations
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula $V(r,t)=\mathbb{E}\left[\exp\left(-\int_{t}^{T}r(\tau)d\tau\right)\times\mbox{Payoff}\right]$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection*
One-factor models
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\frac{\partial V}{\partial t}+\frac{1}{2}w^{2}\frac{\partial^{2}V}{\partial r^{2}}+(u-\lambda w)\frac{\partial V}{\partial r}-rV=0
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Affine solutions for a ZCB of the form 
\begin_inset Formula $V(r,t;T)=\exp(A(t)-rB(t))$
\end_inset

 can be found
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Graphics
	filename one-factor-spot-rate.png

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection*
Multi-factor models 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
dr=udt+wdX_{1}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
dl=pdt+qdX_{2}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\frac{\partial V}{\partial t}+\frac{1}{2}w^{2}\frac{\partial^{2}V}{\partial r^{2}}dt+\frac{1}{2}q^{2}\frac{\partial^{2}V}{\partial l^{2}}dt+\frac{1}{2}\rho wq\frac{\partial^{2}V}{\partial r\partial l}dt+(u-\lambda w)\frac{\partial V}{\partial r}+(p-\lambda_{l}q)\frac{\partial V}{\partial l}-rV=0
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The risk-adjustred drift rates are: 
\begin_inset Formula $u-\lambda w$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $p-\lambda_{l}q$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Affine solution for a ZCB of the form 
\begin_inset Formula $V(r,t;T)=\exp(A(t)-rB(t)-lC(t))$
\end_inset

 can be found
\end_layout

